<div id="outline-container-orgheadline11" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgheadline11"><span class="section-number-2">1</span> Differentiation</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
</div><div id="outline-container-orgheadline10" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgheadline10"><span class="section-number-3">1.1</span> Derivative &#x2013; what is it?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-1">
</div><div id="outline-container-orgheadline6" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgheadline6"><span class="section-number-4">1.1.1</span> Geometric Interpretation</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-1-1-1">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="orgheadline1"></a>What exactly does derivative means<br  /><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-1-1-1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>So when we say that dy/dx we mean that rate of change of y with respective to x.Which means that as x increases or decreses how does y respond</li>
<li>So if we know the ratio then we can could calculate areas by summing the ratios as we go along the points</li>
</ul>
</div></li>
<li><a id="orgheadline2"></a>Why do we always go for limit<sub>dx-&gt;0</sub><br  /><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-1-1-2">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>So we know rate of change of y for rate of change of x.So this relation is valid for a very small value of dx say near to zero.</li>
<li>Practically speaking this reduces our area to a small field so that we can apply general formulas over our equations</li>
</ul>
</div></li>
<li><a id="orgheadline3"></a>Tangent Explination<br  /><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-1-1-3">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><b>Problem</b> Find the tangent to line to y=f(x) at (x<sub>0</sub>, y<sub>0</sub>)</li>
<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_173059_256515tj.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_173059_256515tj.png" /></li>

<li>Any Tangent has a equation y-y<sub>0</sub> =m(x-x<sub>0</sub>) .We know y=f(x) so we know x,x<sub>0</sub> and y,y<sub>0</sub></li>

<li>But we have to know m &#x2013; so define it f'(x<sub>0</sub>) ,the derivative of f at x<sub>0</sub> is the slope of the tangent line to y=f(x) at p&#x2013; that is the derivative of the tangent line</li>

<li>But how do we know that we drew the tangent line or not.So let's say that there exists a line which passes through a point Q.Lets call it as secant line, As Q gets closer to p then it nears to what is called a tangent line

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Tangent Line= Limit(Secant Line PQ) as Q-&gt;P ..here we assume that P is fixed</li>
</ul></li>

<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_174611_25651G4p.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_174611_25651G4p.png" /></li>

<li>limit<sub>dx -&gt; 0</sub> means that as the distance between Q and P gets to 0</li>

<li>So in the above image we can calculate Q as (x<sub>0</sub>+dx) and y=f(x<sub>0</sub>+dx) so we can replace the equation of slope as</li>

<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_175002_25651TCw.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_175002_25651TCw.png" /></li>
</ul>
</div></li>

<li><a id="orgheadline4"></a>Lets do a simple Example<br  /><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-1-1-4">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_175851_25651gM2.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_175851_25651gM2.png" /></li>

<li><b>Lets go For a Practical Example</b>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><i>Find Areas of Triangles Enclosed By Axes and Tangent to (Y=1/x)</i></li>

<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_180619_25651SWF.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_180619_25651SWF.png" /></li>

<li><i>So find the area of the red</i></li>

<li><img src="./Diff.org_20160630_180842_25651fgL.png" alt="Diff.org_20160630_180842_25651fgL.png" /></li>

<li>We need to find the arrow points</li>

<li>so can write the equation of tangent as y-y<sub>0</sub> = m(x-x<sub>0</sub>) but since f(x)=1/x</li>

<li>m=-1/x<sup>2</sup></li>

<li>So then we find x<sub>intercept</sub> which is x when y=0 =&gt; 0-(1/x<sub>0</sub>)=(-1/x<sup>2</sup>)(x-x<sub>0</sub>) =&gt; x=2x<sub>0</sub> =&gt; we can calculate y<sub>intercept</sub> from the above we get y=2y<sub>0</sub></li>

<li>Area = (base*height)/2=(2x<sub>0</sub>)(2y<sub>0</sub>)/2=2*x<sub>0</sub>*y<sub>0</sub></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
</div></li>

<li><a id="orgheadline5"></a>More Notations<br  /><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-1-1-5">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>y=f(x) =&gt; dy=df</li>
<li>f'= df/dx =(d/dx)f =(d/dx)y</li>
</ul>
</div></li></ol>
</div>



